> Is it an absolute requirement that metrics be implemented in mir_eval in order to be called from the jams library? If not, if the translation is simple enough, couldn't you just call appropriate scikit-learn functions from jams directly? If so, I'm curious why, but we don't need to discuss that here.

In principle no, we could write wrappers around a different library. That said, as you can see from the [wrapper code](https://github.com/marl/jams/blob/master/jams/eval.py) all the wrappers are very simple because they just need to get the data in the right format and then they let `mir_eval` take if from there. If we were to wrap around `sklearn` it would involve mimicking the `mir_eval` output structure etc., and I wonder whether that's in/outside the scope of `jams`.

