Hi @WardLT,

first of all, thanks to @JFChen3 and you for all your efforts. Changing Matminers framework to feature a proper class structure is much appreciated in my opinion.

Now, back to our discussion. I don't see the argument with the options because you can simply use [function overloading](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_overloading), which is an elegant way to deal with this.  Consider:

class BaseClass(object):
    def __init__(self):
        self.l = None
    def labels(self):
        if self.l is None:
            raise NotImplementedError("label/s is/are not defined!")
        return self.l
class DerivedClass(BaseClass):
    def __init__(self):
        BaseClass.__init__(self)
        self.l = "My label"
class DerivedClass2(BaseClass):
    def labels(self, p):
        return "Successfully overloaded labels function using parameter {} now.".format(p)
if __name__ == '__main__':
    try:
        BaseClass().labels()
    except NotImplementedError:
        print('Correctly caught exception.')
    print(DerivedClass2().labels('p'))

This yields:

Correctly caught exception.
Successfully overloaded labels function using parameter p now.

Does that make sense?

Also, I don't anticipate that neither the citation nor the implementer is likely to change depending on the option of a featurizer. Can you think of a realistic situation where that might happen? So far, all featurizer classes are based on one (list of) paper(s)---if at all.

